tures (Question 5.2).\n","\n","The average accuracy for logistic regression using all 30 features (around 0.929) is noticeably higher than when using only the two selected features (around 0.897).  This trend is consistent across the Decision Tree and Random Forest models as well, suggesting the importance of other features beyond the top two selected by the chi-squared test.\n","\n","\n","### 2. Data Analysis Key Findings\n","\n","*   Using all 30 features consistently resulted in higher mean accuracy across all three models (Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, and Random Forest) compared to using only the two most important features identified by chi-square testing.  The difference was particularly pronounced for Random Forest (0.970 vs. 0.911 mean accuracy).\n","*   The standard deviation of accuracy was lower for models trained on all features, indicating more stable performance across the 5 folds of cross-validation.\n","*   A final Logistic Regression model trained on the full training dataset achieved a test accuracy of 0.924 on the held-out test set, demonstrating good generalization performance on unseen data.\n","\n","### 3. Insights or Next Steps\n","\n","*   Explore feature engineering techniques to potentially improve model performance, as the models perform significantly better with all features than the top 2 chosen features, implying that the currently used feature engineering is not optimal.\n","*   Investigate other feature selection methods (e.g., recursive feature elimination, LASSO) to determine if different subsets of features provide better results.\n"],"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"U6GpnLbgNSSj"}}]}